statements.1:
The Goal

The goal of the game is to destroy the opponent's base.

  Rules

The game is played between two players on a rectangular 1460x960 map, in simultaneous moves manner. Each player commands his hero and an army of minions aiming to destroy the opponent's base and protect his own. During the game, players take ownership of mines to earn gold that can be spent on buying new troops and improving their quality. The game lasts maximally 200 turns.

Units

There are four types of units: base, hero, minion, and mine. Every unit has the same set of attributes:
  • owner: 0 for our unit, 1 for opponent's, 2 for neutral ones.
  • id: unique identifier of the unit.
  • type: 0 for base, 1 for hero, 2,3,4 for minions.
  • x y: current position of the unit.
  • damage: base amount of damage that unit applies when attacking.
  • health: current health points of the unit. Units with 0 or less health are considered destroyed and removed from the map.
  • vision: the radius around the unit in which it can see other units. Always equal to 100 and the same for all units.
  • range: the radius around the unit in which it can attack opponent's units. Always equal to 70 and the same for all units.
  • speed: maximal distance the unit can cover in a single turn.
Units are just a single point. They do not occupy any space and do not collide with each other.

Bases

Each player contains a single base, located in the corner of the map (0 0 for the first player, 1460 960 for the second player).
A base is immovable, cannot attack and it is always visible to the opponent (even when there is no unit that can see it directly). Initial base attributes are 600 health, 0 damage, and 0 speed.
The first player whose base health reaches 0 or below loses. If both bases are destroyed in the same turn there is a draw. When the game reaches maximal number of turns, a player owning base with more health points wins (or there is a draw if health of both bases is the same).

Minions

Minions can be bought by the players and set to move towards the opponent base. A player has no direct control over a minion. He can only (in the moment of buying) define its route by providing a bending point at some coordinates x y. The minion will spawn at the player's base and travel with constant speed from the base to the bending point, and then from the bending point to the opponent's base.
There are three types of minions: SWORDSMAN (unit type 2), AXEMAN (3), and BOWMAN (4). Each type is stronger than one other and weaker than the remaining type (2 is weaker than 3, 3 is weaker than 4, 4 is weaker than 2). When attacking a weaker unit, the damage is multiplied by 1.5. When attacking a stronger one, the damage multiplier is 0.75.
Regardless of the type, every minion costs 4 gold, and its initial attributes are 36 health, 12 damage, and 54 speed.

Heroes

Each player controls a single hero that is a unit stronger than minions and can be directly controlled. Every turn, a player can order a hero to attack a particular target and to move towards a given point. If no valid target is specified, a hero uses the same autotargeting algorithm as minions (details below).
When hero is destroyed, it can be summoned again, with the full health, at the cost of 40 gold. Initial attributes of a hero are 240 health, 18 damage, and 81 speed.
Before hero is resummoned, his soul remains in the last location he was alive. It is not listed as a unit and cannot attack, but gives visibility for its owner as if he were alive.

Mines

Mines are immobile, indestructible, non-shooting units, which are initially neutral and can change ownership during the game. There are between 5 and 10 mines on each map, placed symmetrically around the centre of the map. If a mine is owned by a player, it gives him 1 gold per turn and visibility in the region.
Ownership of mine is changed when in its range there is at least one other unit of a player and no units of his opponent. Then, this player becomes mine's new owner. In all other cases the owner from the previous turn remain unchanged.

Economy

Each player starts with 40 gold, and receives 1 gold plus 1 gold for each of the owned mines at the end of the turn.
Gold can be spend for buying new minions (4 gold per minion), respawning fallen hero (40 gold), or upgrading attributes of a particular unit type (price depends on the upgrade level). Spending gold is possible after unit moves and fights, but before the current turn income (see exact turn order below).

Upgrades

Attributes of minions and heroes can be upgraded. There are 4 levels of upgrade for each combination of unit type (1, 2, 3, 4) and attribute (health, damage, speed). Level 0 means the default values for the attributes. Each next level increases a value of the attribute for each matching unit that will be bought as well as for the ones already existing on the map.
Upgrade values for minions are as follows. Upgrading to level 1 costs 4 gold, to level 2 - 8 gold, and to level 3 - 12 gold. Corresponding upgrades give: +12 health, +4 damage, +18 speed.
Upgrade values for heroes. Upgrading to level 1 costs 8 gold, to level 2 - 16 gold, and to level 3 - 24 gold. Corresponding upgrades give: +80 health, +6 damage, +27 speed.

Fighting

Fights are resolved simultaneously.
First, every unit chooses its target among the visible opponent's units (regardless of other unit's actions) and reduces the target's health based on the damage attribute value.
In case with fithing against a stronger or weaker opponent, additional damage multipliers are used (0.75 and 1.5 respectively). Otherwise (includes all damage applied by and to heroes and bases) unmodified damage value is used.
Then, all units with health 0 are removed.
Minions choose their targets automatically using the following algorithm. If target given to the hero by the player is invalid, the hero uses the same procedure.
  1. Attack the opponent's base if in range.
  2. Attack the opponent's hero if in range.
  3. Attack the closest opponent's minion that has a weaker type. In case of ties, the minion with lowest id is chosen.
  4. Attack the closest opponent's minion that has an equal type (ties resolved as above).
  5. Attack the closest opponent's minion that has an equal type (ties resolved as above).
For hero, all minion types are treated as equal.

Turn Order

The exact order of events during a turn is:
  1. Minions and heroes chooses their targets and apply damage.
  2. Destroyed units are removed.
  3. Win condition is checked based on the bases health points.
  4. Mines ownership is updated.
  5. Heroes move towards a given target (if not specified, they stay in place). Minions move following their paths. Minions that attacked this turn do not move.
  6. Gold spending actions (buying minions, upgrading units, respawning hero) are applied in order given by the players.
  7. Players gain income.
Victory Conditions
  • Your opponent's base health has dropped to zero.
  • You have more base health points than your opponent after 200 turns.
Defeat Conditions
  • Your base's health reaches zero.
  • Your program does not provide a valid command in time.

Debugging tips

  • Hover over an entity to see extra information about it
  • Use SAY action to print text on the screen
  • Press the gear icon on the viewer to access extra display options
  • Use the keyboard to control the action: space to play/pause, arrows to step 1 frame at a time

Acknowledgments

This contribution was developed for the Polish High Schools Championship in Team Programming 2022.

Authored by Jakub Kowalski (@aCat).

Additional thanks to: @Rogacz, @Illedan, @radekmie, @Gabbek, @DomiKo, eulerscheZahl.



  Game Input

Input for One Game Turn
First line: 2 space-separated integers:
  • myGold: your current gold.
  • opponentGold: your opponent's gold.
Next line: An integer visibleUnits for the number of visible units.
Next visibleUnits lines: 8 space-separated integers to describe each visible unit:
  • owner: 0 if you are the owner of this unit, 1 if it is opponent, 2 if the unit is neutral.
  • id: unique identifier of the unit.
  • type: 0 for base, 1 for hero, 2, 3, 4 for minions, and 5 for mine.
  • x: current x position of the unit.
  • y: current y position of the unit.
  • damage: the value of unit's damage attribute.
  • health: current health points of the unit.
  • speed: the value of unit's speed attribute.
Output
A single line that may contain several actions separated by semi-colon ;. The available actions are:
  • BUY type x y to summon a minion of type type (2 for SWORDSMAN, 3 for AXEMAN, and 4 for BOWMAN) that will go towards the opponent base bending its track at point x y.
  • UPGRADE type attribute to buy next level upgrade for all units of given type (1, 2, 3, or 4) for given attribute (damage, health, speed).
  • COMMAND targetId x y to directly command hero's actions. The hero will attack the opponent unit of id targetId if within range, and go towards the point x y. If an invalid targetId is given, e.g. -1, the hero will choose a default target using the same priorities as minions. At most one such action can be given per turn.
  • RESPAWN to summon fallen hero to your base. Summoned hero will have new id. At most one such action can be given per turn.
  • SAY message to display message on a screen. At most one such action can be given per turn.
Ordering of actions that spend gold is meaningful. If there is not enough gold to perform such an action, it will be skipped.
Example valid action sequence: UPGRADE 4 health ; BUY 3 200 100 ; SAY hello\\ngame ; COMMAND 15 520 600; BUY 4 111 320
Constraints
Response time for first turn 1000ms
Response time for one turn 50ms

  • SAY message to display message on a screen. At most one such action can be given per turn.
Ordering of actions that spend gold is meaningful. If there is not enough gold to perform such an action, it will be skipped.
Example valid action sequence: UPGRADE 4 health ; BUY 3 200 100 ; SAY hello\\ngame ; COMMAND 15 520 600; BUY 4 111 320
Constraints
Response time for first turn 1000ms
Response time for one turn 50ms

INPUT
myGold: My amount of gold
opponentGold: Opponent's amount of gold
visibleUnits: the number of visible units
owner: 0 if you are the owner of this unit, 1 if it is opponent, 2 if the unit is neutral.
id: unique identifier of the unit
type: type of the unit: 0 for base, 1 for hero, 2, 3, 4 for minions, and 5 for mine.
